    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1864770015" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1864770015" />
    <a title="Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24668886-scott"><img alt="Scott" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381636198p2/24668886.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1864770015?book_show_action=true">Jul 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott" href="/user/show/24668886-scott">Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24668886-scott?shelf=stephen-king-scary">stephen-king-scary</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1864770015" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7718970906044837856">** The Stephen King Goodreads Discussion Group is doing a re-read of his works from the beginning to the end. It’s been a long time since I have really immersed myself in Uncle Stevie’s world, but a rate of a book a month, I am all in. My goal is to read and review each one with as much honesty and reflection that I can give. ** <br/><br/>Background – “Four Past Midnight” was originally published in 1990 in hardcover by Viking Press. It is a collection of four novellas similar to his King’s previous work,</span>
  <span id="freeText7718970906044837856" style="display:none">** The Stephen King Goodreads Discussion Group is doing a re-read of his works from the beginning to the end. It’s been a long time since I have really immersed myself in Uncle Stevie’s world, but a rate of a book a month, I am all in. My goal is to read and review each one with as much honesty and reflection that I can give. ** <br /><br />Background – “Four Past Midnight” was originally published in 1990 in hardcover by Viking Press. It is a collection of four novellas similar to his King’s previous work, “Different Seasons”, except this time the stories are horror based with elements of science fiction and the supernatural included. <br /><br />My Kindle and paperback list the length of the combined novellas as 995 and 925 pages, respectively.<br /><br />The four Novella’s include:<br /><br />“The Langoliers” – Airline pilot, Brian Engle, is informed upon landing in Los Angeles that his ex-wife has died in an accidental apartment fire in Boston. Brian finds himself grabbing a red-eye flight cross country that changes his life forever. During the flight Brian awakes to find that all of the crew and most of the passengers are gone – disappeared. Luckily, Brian is able to take over flying the airplane, but soon discovers that he and nine other passengers are all that’s left on the plane. The survivors figure out that they were all asleep when the disappearing act occurred but they have no idea what caused it. To make matters worse, all communications with the ground are dead, leaving them no choice but continue on to Boston, where an even darker presence awaits their arrival… <br /><br />“Secret Window, Secret Garden” – Successful writer, Mort Rainey, is confronted by a stranger at the front door of his lake house, claiming that Mort stole a short story from him. The man, John Shooter, has driven all the way from Mississippi to confront Mort, who denies ever seeing him before or plagiarizing anyone else’s work. Shooter firmly tells Mort that he’s not playing games and leaves a copy of his story “Secret Window, Secret Garden” on Mort’s porch. When Mort gets curious enough to read the story, he unbelievably discovers that it is eerily close to his own story “Sowing Seeds”, previously published in a magazine and then a collection of short-stories. When Mort tries to confront Shooter that he wrote his story first, things take an ugly and dark turn, forcing Mort to face am enemy that cannot be stopped… <br /><br />“The Library Policeman” – Insurance agent, Sam Peebles, gets coerced into giving a speech at his local Rotary Club for their monthly dinner event. His office assistant, Naomi Higgins, listens to a draft of his speech and recommends that he stop by their small- town library to check out a coupe of books that will help provide him some good jokes to liven up his talk. At the library, Sam notices several disturbing posters in the children’s section that bother him, including one of a scary library policeman. He then meets an eccentric librarian, Ardelia Lortz, who helps him find his books, gives him a new library card, and warns to return the books on time or she will send the library policeman after him. However, when Sam mentions his meeting Ardelia, he gets a cold reaction. He is told that Ardelia has been dead for many years… Then to make things worse, Sam loses the library books and the library policeman is set to make him a visit he’ll never forget… <br /><br />“The Sun Dog” – Kevin Delevan celebrates his 15th birthday by receiving a new Sun 660 Polaroid camera from his parents. The only problem is no matter what Kevin takes a picture of, it always turns out the same, that of a vicious black dog standing by a white picket fence. And each time Kevin takes another the picture, the outcome is the evil looking dog turning more towards the camera as if preparing to attack the photographer. To make matters worse, Kevin ends up getting help with understanding the camera from Reggie “Pop” Merrill, an untrustworthy and seedy owner of Castle Rock’s junk shop and loan shark. Pop sees this as an opportunity by stealing the haunted camera and selling it to one of his paranormal enthusiastic customers for a tidy sum of money. However, as more pictures are taken, the dog appears to be transforming into a savage monster getting ready to lunge forward and break through into the real world… 	 <br /><br />Thoughts and Reflections – The first story – “The Langoliers” – was a very enjoyable reading experience, blending drama, science fiction, and a bit of supernatural influences. The characters were three-dimensional, the plotting intense, and the story fast-moving and mesmerizing. For me, the combination of strong characters and forceful story, was an excellent mix. I was especially intrigued by the mysterious and physically imposing Nick Hopewell, drawn to the sensitivity of Lauren Stevenson, and raising my fist in support of heroic Brian Engle. It was the interweaving of their personal storylines playing out against the horrifying sci-fi elements that made this a thrilling ride, and one of my favorite King novellas. Grade: A. <br /><br />The second story – “Secret Window, Secret Garden” – was an absolute crazy blast to read and almost impossible to put down. King has written several times about writers - their struggles, fears, and creative powers. This time he takes on the battle of being accused of plagiarizing the work of others, and takes it to another completely different level. Although foundationally set as a mystery, this story was a page-turning psychological thriller with touches of almost supernatural overtones. King did an amazing job of kicking it off with a mysterious confrontation between Mort and the mysterious Shooter, then building on that conflict with the other challenges that Mort is dealing like the collapse of his marriage, and brought everything to a shocking and explosive ending. In this one he demands your attention immediately in the first paragraph and keeps it all the way until the very last paragraph. There was no letting down at all. For me, this was one of the best novellas that King has written. Really! Grade: A+. <br /><br />The third story – “The Library Policeman” – was a story that I have some real mixed feelings about. It starts off slow and steady, taking a while to introduce the characters and set-up the plot. It eventually gets going and finds it rhythm until about three-fourths of the way through. Then the last quarter pretty much disappointed me. The main villain (monster) was too similar to other creatures that King has used in his other books and stories. The ending left plot points and connections hanging, questions unanswered, and a disjointed wrap-up that felt rather discombobulated. Even worse (and this may be more of a personal thing to me than others), I have never been as grossed out on an emotional level as I was while reading a specific scene that shall go unnamed. Sorry, Uncle Stevie, it was way to graphic for me. It emotionally disturbed me enough that I may not be able to read this story again. Grade: B-. <br /><br />The final story – “The Sun Dog” – was my least favorite of the four. It starts out slow and takes a while to pick up some steam. It didn’t really pull me in and keep my attention. The drama just wasn’t enough, especially when Pops got control of the camera and couldn’t find a buyer among his unique network of customers. For me, the story dragged on too long, spent too much time on secondary scene descriptions, and it could have been edited down to have a tighter delivery. Grade: C-. <br /><br />Other Notes – This collection of novellas won the Bram Stoker Award in 1990 for Best Collection, as well as being nominated for a Locus Award in 1991.<br /><br />Two of the novellas were adapted for television and the big screen. “The Langoliers” was adapted as a two-part ABC-TV movie in 1994. “Secret Window, Secret Garden” was made into a film adaption in 2004 starring Johnny Depp. 	<br /><br />Overall – The first two were well-written novella’s that exemplified why I love King’s writing so much. When he is at his best, he is one of the best. They alone were worth the proverbial price of admission. The last two were on the medium and lower end of the spectrum, showing promise for a bit, and then suffering with plotting challenges and weak endings. For me, two out of four wasn’t bad when those first two were just so dang good. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7718970906044837856" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


