    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2827900720" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2827900720" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25220242-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1383310400p2/25220242.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2827900720?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/25220242-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2827900720" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2350630518335865538">Oh dear. Contrary to the popular opinion of probably many Stephen King fans, I just did not enjoy this one. A collection of four stories, I was sincerely hoping this would fulfil one of my final few Book Bingo categories – a book that scares me. However, I was bored, found it mundane and quite tedious in places. This is a big old novel – close to 1000 pages – and for me, this seemed 500 pages too long!<br/><br/>The stories range in horrors but they do contain the central theme of your worst nightmare. ‘Th</span>
  <span id="freeText2350630518335865538" style="display:none">Oh dear. Contrary to the popular opinion of probably many Stephen King fans, I just did not enjoy this one. A collection of four stories, I was sincerely hoping this would fulfil one of my final few Book Bingo categories – a book that scares me. However, I was bored, found it mundane and quite tedious in places. This is a big old novel – close to 1000 pages – and for me, this seemed 500 pages too long!<br /><br />The stories range in horrors but they do contain the central theme of your worst nightmare. ‘The Langoliers’ was my favourite out of the four and I still remember the television adaptation that was shown many, many years ago. I actually think it was probably better than the book, come to think of it; although rose-tinted glasses and all that, it is likely not to have aged well and wouldn’t be as terrifying as I remember. ‘Secret Window, Secret Garden’ was quite predictable; ‘The Library Policeman’ intends to strike fear into keeping an overdue library book; and ‘The Sun Dog’ felt anti-climactic and far too long for my liking.<br /><br />There is a range of stories in here and if you like to indulge in nightmarish scenes, then this would probably appeal. Lacking subtle suggestions, King lays bare all of his ideas and the dense descriptions intend to intensify the narrative. Yet, I found this far to obvious for my liking and this certainly lessened the horror behind his writing. I am sure I will find a book that scares me and, secondly, a Stephen King book that I actually really enjoy, but at this time, ‘Four Past Midnight’ fell flat. I instead found myself looking forward to completing this read and am now seeking something far more light-hearted.<br /><br />Maybe the horror genre isn’t for me, but I will certainly keep looking. There are a lot of King novels out there and he still remains a popular reader’s choice. Therefore, I will persevere with Stephen King books and rediscover him at a later date. For now, this book left me feeling unfulfilled and lethargic because it struggled to get my heart racing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2350630518335865538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


